mao R Documentation A study of Parkinson’s disease and MAO gene

Description: The markers are both with actual allele sizes and allele numbers. The dataset is distributed with the GENECOUNTING version 2.0 illustrating gene counting method involving chromosome X. A total of 183 patients and 157 controls (150 males, 190 females) were available, together with five markers in MAOA (monoamine oxidase A) region with alleles 12, 9, 6, 5, 3, and the first three markers were genotyped in all individuals while the fourth and fifth were genotyped for 294 and 304 individuals.

Source: Dr Helen Latsoudis of Institute of Psychiatry, KCL

References: Zhao JH (2004). 2LD, GENECOUNTING and HAP: computer programs for linkage disequilibrium analysis. Bioinformatics 20:1325-1326.

Description of the MAO dataset and variables

Parkinson’s disease (PD) is the second most common, age-related neurodegenerative disorder, affecting about 3% of the population by the age of 65 and up to 5% of the people over 85 years (Dexter, D. T. Et al., 2013).

The MAO dataset contains observations over a study of Parkinson’s disease and MAO (monoamine oxidase A) gene using a gene counting method involving chromosome X. Five markers in the MAOA region with alleles 12, 9, 6, 5, 3 are observed in the study.

Description of the variables
Column Type Description
id character Patient ID.
type numeric Type of patient. 1=Patients (183), 0=Control group (157).
gender numeric Patient gender information 0=male (150) , 1=female (190).
age numeric Patients age (years).
aao numeric Patients age at disease onset (years).
aad numeric Patients age at deep brain stimulation (DBS) operation (years).
updrs numeric Unified Parkinson Disease Rating Scale (UPDRS).
maoai2 character Monoamine Oxidase A (MAO-A) gene, imidazoline I2 receptor.
ai2code character MAO-A I2 code.
maobi2 character MAO-A BI2 receptor.
bi2code character MAO-A BI2 code.
gtbex3 character Gene (Protein Coding), Brain Expressed X-Linked 3 (BEX3).
bex3code character BEX3 code.
maoavntr character Variable number of tandem repeats (VNTR), repeated DNA sequences in a genome.
vntrcode character VNTR sequence code.
vntrcod2 character VNTR sequence code 2.
maoa31 character B-cell receptor-associated protein 31 (Bap31), negatively regulates the expression of MAO-A via R1.
mao31cod character MAO-A Bap31 code.
mao31co2 character MAO-A Bap31 code 2.

NOTICE!

Variable descriptions table above mainly consists of definitions available at the Genecards.org. Author of this report has no medical science knowledge. Therefore please refer to the sources listed in the references section for accurate scientific information on monoamine oxidase and human genes.

# install.packages("gap")
library(gap.datasets)
library(tidyverse)
theme_set(theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "top"))
library(dplyr)

Summary statistics on variation of the variables in MAO dataset

data <- mao
# Clean up empty strings
remove_empty <- function(observed) {
  result <- replace(observed, str_trim(observed) == "", NA)
  result
}
data <- data %>% mutate_all(~ remove_empty(.))

# Label the columns type and gender
data$type <- factor(data$type, levels = c("0", "1"), 
                  labels = c("Control", "Patient"))
data$gender <- factor(data$gender, levels = c("0", "1"),
                  labels = c("Male", "Female"))

data %>% 
  group_by(type, gender) %>%
  summarize(count =  n(),
            min_age = min(age, na.rm = TRUE),
            max_age = max(age, na.rm = TRUE),
            mean_age = mean(age, na.rm = TRUE),
            stdev_age = sd(age, na.rm = TRUE))
# Note that data is ignored when age information is unknown.
data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=age)) +
  geom_histogram(colour = "darkgreen", fill = "green", binwidth = 0.3) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.1) +  
  scale_x_sqrt() +
  facet_grid(type~gender) + 
  ggtitle('Distribution density of age by gender in groups Patient and Control') +
  labs(x = "Age of individual") +
  labs(y = "Density of age histogram in group")

NOTICE!

Control group consists significantly younger individuals compared to patients and it has outliers. Control skewed left while patients group skewed right unimodal age distributions. Male patient group has an age distribution which is much close to the normal distribution model than the others.

# maoai2
m1 <- data %>%
  group_by(type, gender, maoai2) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(gene = "maoai2")
m1 <- select(m1, -maoai2)
m1 <- m1 %>%
  group_by(type, gender, gene) %>%
  summarise(n=list(sum(count))) 

m1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(type, n, fill = gender)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Group of individual") +
  labs(y = "Count of individual")

data %>%
  group_by(maoai2,type, gender) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  filter(count > 3) %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(count, maoai2, color=gender, size = count)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~type) +
  labs(x = "Count of individual") +
  labs(y = "Genotyped marker (maoai2)")

Three most genotyped maoai2 gene markers in both P/C groups by gender.

# Most genotyped three maoai2 markers grouped by gender and ties inclusive. Omit null values.
data %>%
  group_by(across(all_of(c('type','gender','maoai2')))) %>%
  filter(all(!is.na(maoai2))) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 3, with_ties = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(gene = 'maoai2', value = maoai2) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, maoai2, fill = maoai2)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  facet_grid(gender~type) +
  labs(y = "Genotyped gene marker") +
  labs(x = "Occurrence count of gene marker")

NOTICE!

Observations of females have double value sets because female humans have a pair of X (XX) chromosomes while human male chromosomes have only one X (XY).

NOTICE!

The maoai2 markers in female control group genotyped with 110/112 appears fairly frequent (26 occurrences, 29.55% in female control, 13.68% in all females) while they appear relatively less in patient group (6 occurrences, 5.88% in female patient, 3.16% in all females. Analysis of data and hypothesis testing.

  • We will test the hypothesis question: ’Does the maoa31 gene genotyped marker’s average occurrence frequency differ between groups?’.
  • Patient group: 81 male and 102 female individuals.
  • Control group: 69 male and 88 female individuals.
  • Test problem: H0 : µX = µY vs Ha : µX ̸= µY.
  • Idea: Reject null hypothesis if ¯x − ¯y is large.
# maoa31_freq
maoa31_freq <- data %>%
  group_by(across(all_of(c('type','gender','maoa31')))) %>%
  filter(!is.na(maoa31)) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(freq = n/sum(n))

maoa31_freq
# For Student's t-test, specify the option var.equal=TRUE:
ttest <- t.test(freq ~ type, data = maoa31_freq
              , var.equal = TRUE
              , conf.level = 0.95)
ttest
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  freq by type
## t = 0.75165, df = 69, p-value = 0.4548
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Control and group Patient is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.02401114  0.05304340
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Control mean in group Patient 
##            0.06451613            0.05000000
  • t is the t-test statistic value (t = 0.75165),
  • df is the degrees of freedom (df= 69),
  • p-value is the significance level of the t-test (p-value = 0.4548).
  • conf.int is the confidence interval of the means difference at 95% (conf.int = [-0.02401114,0.05304340]);
  • sample estimates is the mean value of the sample (mean = 0.06451613, 0.05000000).
  • alpha = 0.05 < 0.4548 thus we retain the null hypothesis.

NOTICE!

The p-value of the test is 0.4548, which is higher than the significance level alpha = 0.05, indicates strong evidence for the null hypothesis. This means we retain the null hypothesis and reject the alternative hypothesis. We can conclude that maoa31 gene genotyped marker’s average occurrence frequency difference is statistically insignificant between patient and control groups. This means that no effect was observed.
